        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Here's a workaround I'm currently using.\n\nEnsure `/` is empty on startup.\n\n```lua\nvim.api.nvim_create_autocmd(\"VimEnter\", {\n  callback = function() vim.fn.setreg(\"/\", {}) end\n})\n```\n\nCheck if `/` is empty before performing `n` (the same can be done for `N`).\n```lua\nvim.keymap.set(\n  {\"n\", \"x\"},\n  \"n\",\n  [[@/ == '' ? ':echo \"/ is empty\"<Cr>' : 'n']],\n  { expr = true, noremap = true, silent = true }\n)\n```\n\nFinally, override `<C-l>` to clear `/`.\n\n```lua\nvim.keymap.set(\n  \"n\",\n  \"<C-l>\",\n  [[<C-l>:<C-u>call setreg('/', [])<Cr>]],\n  { noremap = true, silent = true }\n)\n```",
